self-limits as opportunities

00:03:40.590 --> 00:03:45.000
to creatively trespass-- to
maybe add something that wasn't

00:03:45.000 --> 00:03:48.248
there and enliven not just
myself, but colleagues

00:03:48.248 --> 00:03:50.040
and the mission and
vision of the companies

00:03:50.040 --> 00:03:50.850
that I worked for.

00:03:53.440 --> 00:03:57.270
So, anybody here go to
contemporary art museums?

00:03:57.270 --> 00:03:58.390
OK, about 50%.

00:03:58.390 --> 00:04:00.940
And somebody is like, meh,
only if it's free day.

00:04:00.940 --> 00:04:02.570
That's fine.

00:04:02.570 --> 00:04:03.560
That's fine.

00:04:03.560 --> 00:04:06.310
I sort of felt like, meh,
when somebody offered me

00:04:06.310 --> 00:04:07.930
a job in a contemporary
art museum.

00:04:07.930 --> 00:04:09.692
I'm like, I don't
understand the rules.

00:04:09.692 --> 00:04:11.650
They're always saying
like, don't touch things.

00:04:11.650 --> 00:04:14.233
And then it's contemporary art
so they're like, why aren't you

00:04:14.233 --> 00:04:14.950
touching it?

00:04:14.950 --> 00:04:16.660
Very confusing.

00:04:16.660 --> 00:04:20.950
And they wanted somebody, like
a rule-breaker from the outside

00:04:20.950 --> 00:04:24.850
to come inside and
create wild programs

00:04:24.850 --> 00:04:28.840
and generate new revenue streams
and increase attendance--

00:04:28.840 --> 00:04:32.350
pretty regular metrics
for functioning, right?

00:04:32.350 --> 00:04:34.960
And so, I got there
and I started--

00:04:34.960 --> 00:04:38.200
I did what I do in theater,
that's my background.

00:04:38.200 --> 00:04:39.610
You sort of assess
the situation.

00:04:39.610 --> 00:04:42.280
You're like, who's my audience,
what do I have to work with,

00:04:42.280 --> 00:04:43.510
what are the props?

00:04:43.510 --> 00:04:46.210
And I realized there
was this weird thing

00:04:46.210 --> 00:04:49.490
I've never heard of called
Employee of the Month.

00:04:49.490 --> 00:04:51.810
Anybody familiar with it?

00:04:51.810 --> 00:04:53.860
I'm like, Employee of the Month?

00:04:53.860 --> 00:04:55.600
That sounds fantastic.

00:04:55.600 --> 00:04:57.650
How do I win that?

00:04:57.650 --> 00:05:00.430
And you're laughing-- again,
HR was like, Tania, you

00:05:00.430 --> 00:05:02.860
don't win it, you earn it.

00:05:02.860 --> 00:05:07.147
And I was like, then I will
earn your vote and win it.

00:05:07.147 --> 00:05:08.230
And here's what happened--

00:05:08.230 --> 00:05:08.890
I'll show you.

00:06:01.060 --> 00:06:04.630
So, the program I created was
called "Out of the Cubicle,"

00:06:04.630 --> 00:06:06.400
because I was like--

00:06:06.400 --> 00:06:08.540
they brought me into to
think outside the box,

00:06:08.540 --> 00:06:09.790
they stuffed me in a cubicle--

00:06:09.790 --> 00:06:12.590
ironic or scary,
it's a fine line.

00:06:12.590 --> 00:06:18.040
And I decided to create a
programmatic area online

00:06:18.040 --> 00:06:21.610
where people could see that
those of us who thought museums

00:06:21.610 --> 00:06:24.220
are kind of sterile and the
rules, I don't understand,

00:06:24.220 --> 00:06:26.470
and am I OK to go in?

00:06:26.470 --> 00:06:27.950
Will I fit in?

00:06:27.950 --> 00:06:30.730
I created this program where
I ran around the offices

00:06:30.730 --> 00:06:32.590
and actually got to
know my colleagues

00:06:32.590 --> 00:06:35.650
and made these videos that
expose the fact that art

00:06:35.650 --> 00:06:39.070
museums, just like any
other office culture,

00:06:39.070 --> 00:06:41.740
are unique and
boring and exciting

00:06:41.740 --> 00:06:43.340
and everything in between.

00:06:43.340 --> 00:06:46.180
And so, people started
watching this program--

00:06:46.180 --> 00:06:49.270
they came in through the United
States, than other countries.

00:06:49.270 --> 00:06:52.390
And so, I was doing
my job, essentially.

00:06:52.390 --> 00:06:55.780
But here's the critique
that people had--

00:06:55.780 --> 00:06:58.000
and this was a corporately
structured museum.

00:06:58.000 --> 00:06:59.770
There were probably
200 employees

00:06:59.770 --> 00:07:01.930
and there were lots of rules.

00:07:01.930 --> 00:07:07.070
And I said, working and fun,
they're not mutually exclusive.

00:07:07.070 --> 00:07:11.090
And then I showed
them why they're not.

00:07:11.090 --> 00:07:13.180
So, I did lunch
programs in the museum--

00:07:13.180 --> 00:07:15.200
that was part of my job.

00:07:15.200 --> 00:07:16.940
I increased revenue streams.

00:07:16.940 --> 00:07:19.333
So, not only did people
come in through the videos,

00:07:19.333 --> 00:07:21.250
but they literally wanted
to come and see what

00:07:21.250 --> 00:07:23.080
was happening in the museum.

00:07:23.080 --> 00:07:26.530
I also created a program
called Arm Wrestling for Art--

00:07:26.530 --> 00:07:27.880
crazy.

00:07:27.880 --> 00:07:30.430
Where I used my teeny
tiny, nonprofit budget

00:07:30.430 --> 00:07:33.550
to buy an arm wrestling table--
because that makes sense.

00:07:33.550 --> 00:07:36.340
And then, we put it in
the middle of the museum--

00:07:36.340 --> 00:07:39.610
because the problem I
was trying to solve was,

00:07:39.610 --> 00:07:41.890
who here likes art?

00:07:41.890 --> 00:07:44.800
Who here can afford to buy
the art that they really like?

00:07:44.800 --> 00:07:46.090
All the hands go down.

00:07:46.090 --> 00:07:48.220
And I thought, how
do we democratize

00:07:48.220 --> 00:07:49.810
the acquiring of art?

00:07:49.810 --> 00:07:52.210
How do we make art
accessible for everyone?

00:07:52.210 --> 00:07:54.160
What do museums not do?

00:07:54.160 --> 00:07:55.750
They don't give away art.

00:07:55.750 --> 00:07:58.060
And so I thought, let's
make people sweat it out

00:07:58.060 --> 00:07:59.830
and arm wrestle
for a piece of art.

00:07:59.830 --> 00:08:01.095
That seems fair.

00:08:01.095 --> 00:08:02.470
That's how we'd
solve the problem

00:08:02.470 --> 00:08:06.530
as kids, that's how we're
going to do it as adults.

00:08:06.530 --> 00:08:08.590
So, we increased
attendance numbers.

00:08:08.590 --> 00:08:09.220
That's my job.

00:08:09.220 --> 00:08:10.540
Brand awareness--
everybody started

00:08:10.540 --> 00:08:12.400
to know about Scottsdale
Museum of Contemporary Art.

00:08:12.400 --> 00:08:14.140
It's a small
contemporary art museum,

00:08:14.140 --> 00:08:16.120
but it had all of this
new life and people

00:08:16.120 --> 00:08:18.430
coming through the doors
and through the videos.

00:08:18.430 --> 00:08:22.720
Earned media, which anybody in
marketing knows, you pay a lot

00:08:22.720 --> 00:08:24.970
and then you're like, oh
that didn't have an impact.

00:08:24.970 --> 00:08:27.300
We didn't go viral.

00:08:27.300 --> 00:08:29.050
So, we just earn it
the old fashioned way.

00:08:29.050 --> 00:08:30.133
And then you drop the mic.

00:08:33.700 --> 00:08:38.620
So, once upon a time, I was
giving a talk at a startup

00:08:38.620 --> 00:08:42.403
week, and these two engineers
from American Express

00:08:42.403 --> 00:08:43.570
came up to me after my talk.

00:08:43.570 --> 00:08:45.610
They're all like, oh, my god,
that was so cool-- creativity,

00:08:45.610 --> 00:08:46.310
blah blah blah.

00:08:46.310 --> 00:08:48.310
And they're like, we want
to start an innovation

00:08:48.310 --> 00:08:52.210
lab in our company, but we
have no buy-in from our boss,

00:08:52.210 --> 00:08:55.480
no money, no space, and nobody
thinks it's a good idea.

00:08:55.480 --> 00:08:58.570
What's your solve, Tania?

00:08:58.570 --> 00:09:00.100
Oh, my gosh.

00:09:00.100 --> 00:09:02.150
I'm like-- totally easy.

00:09:02.150 --> 00:09:05.950
I'm going to introduce you to
an artist named Meg Dogood.

00:09:05.950 --> 00:09:08.350
So, Meg lives in Chicago.

00:09:08.350 --> 00:09:09.800
She had a dream.

00:09:09.800 --> 00:09:13.070
Her dream was to have four
walls, a gallery space.

00:09:13.070 --> 00:09:13.570
That's it.

00:09:13.570 --> 00:09:16.090
She wanted four walls to be
able to put people's artwork

00:09:16.090 --> 00:09:17.540
in from around the world.

00:09:17.540 --> 00:09:18.580
She had no money.

00:09:18.580 --> 00:09:20.110
She was like a
full-time artist--

00:09:20.110 --> 00:09:23.770
no patrons, no space, no buy-in,
no American Express card,

00:09:23.770 --> 00:09:24.910
I'm certain.

00:09:24.910 --> 00:09:28.480
And here's what she did
to solve that problem--

00:09:28.480 --> 00:09:30.220
she didn't have
the limiting belief

00:09:30.220 --> 00:09:33.080
that the guys at
American Express had.

00:09:33.080 --> 00:09:35.570
So, she created Clutch Gallery.

00:09:35.570 --> 00:09:39.340
It's a 25 square inch space
in the heart of her purse.

00:09:41.890 --> 00:09:46.000
It's totally absurd
and wackily wonderful.

00:09:46.000 --> 00:09:48.007
And so, she solved a problem.

00:09:48.007 --> 00:09:49.840
And I'll show you one
of her installations--

00:09:49.840 --> 00:09:50.715
it's a painting show.

00:09:54.220 --> 00:09:57.910
And so, it just goes to
show you that had she

00:09:57.910 --> 00:10:00.980
had the same limiting belief--
like I don't have money.

00:10:00.980 --> 00:10:02.380
I don't have space.

00:10:02.380 --> 00:10:03.820
I don't have buy-in.

00:10:03.820 --> 00:10:06.490
She never would have created
this innovative space.

00:10:06.490 --> 00:10:09.670
And artists love the challenge
of trying to create artwork

00:10:09.670 --> 00:10:11.690
for 25 by 25 square inches.

00:10:15.150 --> 00:10:16.240
I know.

00:10:16.240 --> 00:10:17.400
OK.

00:10:17.400 --> 00:10:20.940
So, who here went
to first grade?

00:10:20.940 --> 00:10:21.450
Great.

00:10:21.450 --> 00:10:24.310
I knew we'd have
something in common.

00:10:24.310 --> 00:10:25.530
So, I went to first grade.

00:10:25.530 --> 00:10:27.983
I was five years old, which
was younger than the kids--

00:10:27.983 --> 00:10:30.150
not because I was real
smart, but because my parents

00:10:30.150 --> 00:10:32.040
had sex at a certain
period of time

00:10:32.040 --> 00:10:34.510
and I was born in September.

00:10:34.510 --> 00:10:36.300
So there was no
like, she's so smart.

00:10:36.300 --> 00:10:39.300
So, I was younger than the
other kids and I was like--

00:10:39.300 --> 00:10:42.030
I was super chubby, but it
was all focused in my belly.

00:10:42.030 --> 00:10:44.930
So it was like I
had a gut, you know?

00:10:44.930 --> 00:10:49.430
And I wore eyeglasses.

00:10:49.430 --> 00:10:52.460
Anybody wear eyeglasses as a
four or five, six-year-old?

00:10:52.460 --> 00:10:53.720
Fantastic.

00:10:53.720 --> 00:10:56.330
We thought we were really cool.

00:10:56.330 --> 00:10:58.700
My mom said, you're cute, Tania.

00:10:58.700 --> 00:11:00.620
I felt sophisticated
and more intellectual

00:11:00.620 --> 00:11:02.460
than my counterparts.

00:11:02.460 --> 00:11:04.100
I was ready to rock.

00:11:04.100 --> 00:11:07.700
So, I get on the school bus for
the first day of first grade

00:11:07.700 --> 00:11:10.490
and I'm like, I'm
looking good, what?

00:11:10.490 --> 00:11:13.280
I've got my glasses, and
I'm just rock and roll.

00:11:13.280 --> 00:11:14.920
Like oh.

00:11:14.920 --> 00:11:17.640
But, there didn't seem to
be any early adopters of me.

00:11:17.640 --> 00:11:20.050
That's fine.

00:11:20.050 --> 00:11:24.170
And so, I get on the bus and I
see a girl who's about my age--

00:11:24.170 --> 00:11:25.670
and the bus is
about to take off--

00:11:25.670 --> 00:11:27.867
so I slide into one of
those pleather benches

00:11:27.867 --> 00:11:28.700
and sit next to her.

00:11:28.700 --> 00:11:30.920
And I'm like, let the day begin.

00:11:30.920 --> 00:11:33.590
And she looks me square
in the eye and I'm like--

00:11:33.590 --> 00:11:35.890
I like this assertiveness.

00:11:35.890 --> 00:11:40.160
And she's like, four eyes.

00:11:40.160 --> 00:11:41.290
I know.

00:11:41.290 --> 00:11:45.260
So, every single day of
the first week of school

00:11:45.260 --> 00:11:49.010
I get on the bus and I try
to avoid the child tyrant.

00:11:49.010 --> 00:11:50.390
I'd find a seat over here.

00:11:50.390 --> 00:11:54.410
And somehow, that little menace
managed to sneak in and call me

00:11:54.410 --> 00:11:55.520
four eyes.

00:11:55.520 --> 00:12:01.380
And I was like sad and lonely
and didn't know what to do.

00:12:01.380 --> 00:12:02.960
So, I consulted my mom.

00:12:02.960 --> 00:12:09.980
And my mom was like Tania,
four eyes are better than two.

00:12:09.980 --> 00:12:14.430
And I'm like, not only does
that little girl suck at math,

00:12:14.430 --> 00:12:16.840
but she sucks at life.

00:12:16.840 --> 00:12:19.655
And so I was like,
great, I'm armed

00:12:19.655 --> 00:12:22.220
and I'm ready to rock and roll.

00:12:22.220 --> 00:12:25.550
And so I get on the bus
with my newfound phrase

00:12:25.550 --> 00:12:28.310
and I sit next to
her on purpose.

00:12:28.310 --> 00:12:30.680
And she's like, four
eyes, and I'm like,

00:12:30.680 --> 00:12:33.290
four eyes are better than two.

00:12:33.290 --> 00:12:37.200
And she said, no, they're not.

00:12:37.200 --> 00:12:39.970
And I said nothing.

00:12:39.970 --> 00:12:41.220
I had no comeback at all.

00:12:41.220 --> 00:12:42.990
The good news is that I grew up.

00:12:42.990 --> 00:12:44.592
And, oh, somebody--
I was talking

00:12:44.592 --> 00:12:46.800
about this story the other
day and somebody was like,

00:12:46.800 --> 00:12:48.480
what happened to
this little girl?

00:12:48.480 --> 00:12:52.885
And I'm like, well, you know she
didn't invent Google Glass, OK?

00:12:52.885 --> 00:12:54.510
She's not a co-founder
of Warby Parker.

00:12:57.150 --> 00:13:01.320
But what I've learned over
years of being in the world

00:13:01.320 --> 00:13:06.550
is that little critic is not
only on the outside of us,

00:13:06.550 --> 00:13:09.990
but a lot of times we have
that little child tyrant

00:13:09.990 --> 00:13:11.850
on the inside of us.

00:13:11.850 --> 00:13:16.770
And also what I've learned is
that when we see her or him

00:13:16.770 --> 00:13:22.180
or non-gender binary person and
we acknowledge and we say, OK,

00:13:22.180 --> 00:13:24.030
I see you, and we let go--

00:13:24.030 --> 00:13:25.745
that's super helpful.

00:13:25.745 --> 00:13:27.120
And I learned
another thing too--

00:13:27.120 --> 00:13:30.930
that nobody writes
books or plays

00:13:30.930 --> 00:13:36.555
or makes software for or
about anybody who's perfect.

00:13:36.555 --> 00:13:38.430
You wouldn't want to
read a book if everybody

00:13:38.430 --> 00:13:40.680
fit in and was perfect.

00:13:40.680 --> 00:13:43.265
To be perfect or to fit
in is to be invisible.

00:13:43.265 --> 00:13:44.890
And I just didn't
want to be invisible.

00:13:44.890 --> 00:13:46.973
So, that was a really good
moment for me to learn.

00:13:46.973 --> 00:13:48.540
That's me.

00:13:48.540 --> 00:13:51.090
Stop it right now.

00:13:51.090 --> 00:13:52.240
Is my mom here?

00:13:54.930 --> 00:13:57.718
And, clearly, I was going to
audition for the Village People

00:13:57.718 --> 00:13:58.260
the next day.

00:14:01.460 --> 00:14:03.220
Oh, my gosh.

00:14:03.220 --> 00:14:04.100
OK.

00:14:04.100 --> 00:14:07.220
So, at some point
in my career, I

00:14:07.220 --> 00:14:10.910
received a phone call from a
software company named AxoSoft.

00:14:10.910 --> 00:14:13.928
And they were like, Tania,
we've seen you performing

00:14:13.928 --> 00:14:15.470
and presenting around
town, we'd like

00:14:15.470 --> 00:14:17.300
to talk to you about software.

00:14:17.300 --> 00:14:19.100
And I'm like software?

00:14:19.100 --> 00:14:20.810
That sounds awesome.

00:14:20.810 --> 00:14:23.930
I don't know what
they're talking about.

00:14:23.930 --> 00:14:26.690
I love cashmere.

00:14:26.690 --> 00:14:30.930
And so, I took a leap of faith.

00:14:30.930 --> 00:14:31.453
I really do.

00:14:31.453 --> 00:14:33.620
But I can't afford it, so
I go to second-hand stores

00:14:33.620 --> 00:14:34.190
and purchase it.

00:14:34.190 --> 00:14:34.690
Thank you.

00:14:38.240 --> 00:14:39.920
So, I took a leap of
faith and I decided

00:14:39.920 --> 00:14:42.150
to meet with this
software company.

00:14:42.150 --> 00:14:45.800
And I met with the CEO at
the time, Lawdan Shojaee.

00:14:45.800 --> 00:14:47.592
She's like, we really
like your energy.

00:14:47.592 --> 00:14:48.800
That's why we brought you in.

00:14:48.800 --> 00:14:51.440
And I'm like, I like your
energy, that's why I came in.

00:14:51.440 --> 00:14:53.315
She's like, but we're
not offering you a job.

00:14:53.315 --> 00:14:54.660
And I'm like, OK, why am I here?

00:14:54.660 --> 00:14:55.862
I don't understand.

00:14:55.862 --> 00:14:57.320
And she's like,
we've always wanted

00:14:57.320 --> 00:14:59.420
to have a brand evangelist.

00:14:59.420 --> 00:15:02.210
You would make a
great evangelist.

00:15:02.210 --> 00:15:05.470
And I was like,
that would totally

00:15:05.470 --> 00:15:07.510
freak my Jewish mom out.

00:15:07.510 --> 00:15:08.320
Yeah.

00:15:08.320 --> 00:15:10.097
I want to be an evangelist.

00:15:10.097 --> 00:15:10.930
Can I get a witness?

00:15:14.800 --> 00:15:19.600
And so, I started work at
this company, and my first day

00:15:19.600 --> 00:15:23.960
on the job I was like, what
is this magical software we're

00:15:23.960 --> 00:15:24.460
selling?

00:15:24.460 --> 00:15:26.770
Is it like a tool
for telling stories?

00:15:26.770 --> 00:15:29.350
Is it a magical
paintbrush that allows

00:15:29.350 --> 00:15:31.300
artists to make work on wall?

00:15:31.300 --> 00:15:32.020
What is it?

00:15:32.020 --> 00:15:36.580
And she was like, oh, it's a
B2B project management software

00:15:36.580 --> 00:15:38.050
for software developers.

00:15:38.050 --> 00:15:41.750
And I was like trapped
in slow motion,

00:15:41.750 --> 00:15:44.620
like, what are you saying?

00:15:44.620 --> 00:15:48.500
I don't understand that.

00:15:48.500 --> 00:15:52.540
And soon, I learned I didn't
understand a lot of stuff.

00:15:52.540 --> 00:15:55.570
You know, I would hear
people talking about AI

00:15:55.570 --> 00:15:59.320
and I was like, oh, that's when
a British person is at a pub

00:15:59.320 --> 00:16:00.490
and they ask for more beer.

00:16:00.490 --> 00:16:03.400
They're like, I would
like another point.

00:16:03.400 --> 00:16:05.500
That's not the case.

00:16:05.500 --> 00:16:07.600
I also heard people
talking about-- they

00:16:07.600 --> 00:16:09.850
were like, open source,
open source, open source--

00:16:09.850 --> 00:16:12.430
and I'm like, don't
kiss that person.

00:16:12.430 --> 00:16:17.830
I'm pretty sure that
that's no bueno.

00:16:17.830 --> 00:16:19.640
So, I had a lot
of learning to do.

00:16:19.640 --> 00:16:21.430
And, unfortunately--
and fortunately--

00:16:21.430 --> 00:16:23.680
within the first two months
of being there and knowing

00:16:23.680 --> 00:16:26.620
absolutely very
little about software,

00:16:26.620 --> 00:16:29.320
my boss came to a
colleague and I and said,

00:16:29.320 --> 00:16:32.320
we are going to host a
girls in technology event.

00:16:32.320 --> 00:16:34.840
It's an inaugural one, and I
want to show up in a big way,

00:16:34.840 --> 00:16:37.870
so come up with a big idea
around women in technology.

00:16:37.870 --> 00:16:41.710
This is April 2015 just
to give some context

00:16:41.710 --> 00:16:47.020
So, my colleague and I
Sara, we're brainstorming.

00:16:47.020 --> 00:16:49.060
Came up with nothing.

00:16:49.060 --> 00:16:52.300
Then I went for a
little walk and I

00:16:52.300 --> 00:16:55.120
started thinking about
women in the tech space

00:16:55.120 --> 00:16:57.400
and women in lots
of spaces and how,

00:16:57.400 --> 00:17:00.730
a lot of times, we're not
seen, heard, or celebrated

00:17:00.730 --> 00:17:02.350
for the superheroes we are.

00:17:02.350 --> 00:17:05.230
And so, I came up
with this symbol--

00:17:05.230 --> 00:17:07.819
I didn't come up with her, she's
been around for a long time.

00:17:07.819 --> 00:17:09.708
The bathroom lady-- she's here.

00:17:09.708 --> 00:17:10.750
She's made an appearance.

00:17:10.750 --> 00:17:11.920
I've seen her twice today.

00:17:11.920 --> 00:17:14.349
Thank you.

00:17:14.349 --> 00:17:17.619
And I knew that this
symbol was immediately

00:17:17.619 --> 00:17:20.839
recognizable across
cultures, across genders.

00:17:20.839 --> 00:17:22.720
And I didn't know anything else.

00:17:22.720 --> 00:17:23.770
I just had like--

00:17:23.770 --> 00:17:26.140
it wasn't even an idea,
it was just a symbol.

00:17:26.140 --> 00:17:30.610
And I brought the symbol back
to my colleague and I'm like,

00:17:30.610 --> 00:17:31.510
here she is.

00:17:31.510 --> 00:17:33.550
And my colleague's like, OK.

00:17:33.550 --> 00:17:35.150
And that was sort of that.

00:17:35.150 --> 00:17:36.650
But I couldn't shake
the fact that--

00:17:36.650 --> 00:17:38.800
see the shape of her dress?

00:17:38.800 --> 00:17:40.360
It's a triangle.

00:17:40.360 --> 00:17:43.900
And I thought, gosh,
yeah, it's a dress,

00:17:43.900 --> 00:17:47.890
and it looks kind of
like the shape of a cape.

00:17:47.890 --> 00:17:51.260
And so I printed out the
vector and made a few lines

00:17:51.260 --> 00:17:54.150
and then I'm like,
see it right there.

00:17:54.150 --> 00:17:58.035
And AxoSoft-- we came
up with the campaign--

00:17:58.035 --> 00:17:58.910
It Was Never a Dress.

00:17:58.910 --> 00:18:01.077
And I will show you what
happened with it, because I

00:18:01.077 --> 00:18:03.900
