00:26:15.150 --> 00:26:17.730
that we're all leaping with you.

00:26:17.730 --> 00:26:20.520
I think that's helpful to know.

00:26:20.520 --> 00:26:24.310
I would love to engage in a
little questions and answers.

00:26:24.310 --> 00:26:26.980
And, if you have no questions,
I'll ask you questions,

00:26:26.980 --> 00:26:29.840
but I don't think you're
going to want that.

00:26:29.840 --> 00:26:30.340
I'm kidding.

00:26:30.340 --> 00:26:31.380
I'm kidding.

00:26:31.380 --> 00:26:32.906
I'm totally kidding.

00:26:32.906 --> 00:26:36.858
AUDIENCE: Oh, I was like,
oh, you're very intuitive.

00:26:40.140 --> 00:26:41.240
How do you write a book?

00:26:41.240 --> 00:26:44.020
TANIA KATAN: How do
you write a book?

00:26:44.020 --> 00:26:45.900
This is actually something
that I write about

00:26:45.900 --> 00:26:47.310
in "Creative Trespassing"--
whether you're

00:26:47.310 --> 00:26:49.410
wanting to write a book
or make a career shift

00:26:49.410 --> 00:26:52.440
or actually try on a
different role, you start.

00:26:59.090 --> 00:27:03.870
And so, you write a
few lines about what

00:27:03.870 --> 00:27:05.490
you think the book is about.

00:27:05.490 --> 00:27:07.290
Maybe you write a
few lines about what

00:27:07.290 --> 00:27:09.240
you want your next
job to look like

00:27:09.240 --> 00:27:12.120
or what you want your
next project to look like.

00:27:12.120 --> 00:27:15.000
And then you leave it
for a day, and then you

00:27:15.000 --> 00:27:16.260
come back a day later.

00:27:16.260 --> 00:27:18.900
And then you don't look at
it and you write some more.

00:27:18.900 --> 00:27:21.240
So, this is how I've
written this book,

00:27:21.240 --> 00:27:24.210
and this is how a lot of
authors that I know write

00:27:24.210 --> 00:27:27.488
is they write a little a lot.

00:27:27.488 --> 00:27:28.530
You know what I'm saying?

00:27:28.530 --> 00:27:33.240
And if you're thinking about
or you already have a practice

00:27:33.240 --> 00:27:36.420
of writing in a journal or
writing a book or whatever,

00:27:36.420 --> 00:27:39.660
a lot of times we have this
self-limiting belief that we

00:27:39.660 --> 00:27:42.420
put ourselves on a schedule
and if we do not adhere to that

00:27:42.420 --> 00:27:44.490
schedule, we will just stop--

00:27:44.490 --> 00:27:46.320
game over.

00:27:46.320 --> 00:27:49.350
And I would suggest
to you that you--

00:27:49.350 --> 00:27:52.140
even if you mess up
your own schedule

00:27:52.140 --> 00:27:54.000
that only you gave you--

00:27:54.000 --> 00:27:57.960
that you forgive
yourself and continue on.

00:27:57.960 --> 00:27:59.370
So, do a little a lot.

00:27:59.370 --> 00:28:02.550
And also, I find that
accountability-- for me,

00:28:02.550 --> 00:28:07.162
personally, I like to have my
personal board of directors

00:28:07.162 --> 00:28:09.120
that I'm like, you guys,
here's what I'm doing.

00:28:09.120 --> 00:28:11.490
I will send you
some pages, I don't

00:28:11.490 --> 00:28:12.990
need you to read
them, I just you

00:28:12.990 --> 00:28:14.430
need to know they're coming.

00:28:14.430 --> 00:28:16.597
Or I need you to read them
and I need some feedback,

00:28:16.597 --> 00:28:17.940
I need to beta test these ideas.

00:28:17.940 --> 00:28:21.090
Very keen of beta testing
lives and projects--

00:28:21.090 --> 00:28:22.800
love it.

00:28:22.800 --> 00:28:24.810
So, yeah.

00:28:24.810 --> 00:28:26.630
That's a little a lot.

00:28:26.630 --> 00:28:28.180
Yeah, thanks, Kate.

00:28:28.180 --> 00:28:29.837
AUDIENCE: I was
curious about when

00:28:29.837 --> 00:28:31.920
you were saying you were
getting criticism around,

00:28:31.920 --> 00:28:33.628
oh, she's just running
around having fun.

00:28:33.628 --> 00:28:36.840
And how you felt about that
whether you were just like--

00:28:36.840 --> 00:28:39.825
blew it off because you have
all those checked boxes of I'm

00:28:39.825 --> 00:28:43.407
so great, or did
that feel bad to you?

00:28:43.407 --> 00:28:44.490
I'm curious what you felt.

00:28:44.490 --> 00:28:46.050
TANIA KATAN: That's
a great question.

00:28:46.050 --> 00:28:47.650
All of the above.

00:28:47.650 --> 00:28:49.950
And I remember, actually,
when that news was delivered.

00:28:49.950 --> 00:28:54.990
We were in an all-hands meeting
for just the museum staff.

00:28:54.990 --> 00:28:57.300
And there were like
20 of us there,

00:28:57.300 --> 00:28:59.460
and my boss sort of
delivered the news--

00:28:59.460 --> 00:29:01.830
like there are people who
are really concerned who

00:29:01.830 --> 00:29:04.260
find you problematic.

00:29:04.260 --> 00:29:07.080
And he's like, and I want
you to know, I got your back.

00:29:07.080 --> 00:29:09.510
And then I made a
realization-- because it hurt.

00:29:09.510 --> 00:29:11.550
I mean, we're human
beings, right?

00:29:11.550 --> 00:29:13.710
When somebody says,
hey, all the effort

00:29:13.710 --> 00:29:18.900
that you're putting into
making this organization better

00:29:18.900 --> 00:29:20.380
is not right.

00:29:20.380 --> 00:29:21.930
You're not doing
it the right way.

00:29:21.930 --> 00:29:23.190
I felt hurt.

00:29:23.190 --> 00:29:25.287
I felt like, oh,
my gosh, this is

00:29:25.287 --> 00:29:27.662
the only way I know how to
contribute and blah blah blah.

00:29:27.662 --> 00:29:29.640
It was great that
my boss had my back.

00:29:29.640 --> 00:29:34.230
And I also learned something
that was freaky and unexpected

00:29:34.230 --> 00:29:36.180
which was that joy
is actually really

00:29:36.180 --> 00:29:38.820
confrontational to people
who are not choosing

00:29:38.820 --> 00:29:41.070
to live within a state of joy.

00:29:41.070 --> 00:29:44.040
And that was both disheartening
and really powerful

00:29:44.040 --> 00:29:46.140
information.

00:29:46.140 --> 00:29:49.230
So, that's why I sort of
preach the good word of joy,

00:29:49.230 --> 00:29:51.300
because it is a mindset
and it's something

00:29:51.300 --> 00:29:55.920
we can choose, even in rigid,
rule-bound environments.

00:29:55.920 --> 00:29:58.980
It's really the only
thing that we have.

00:29:58.980 --> 00:29:59.480
Thank you.

00:30:04.716 --> 00:30:07.780
AUDIENCE: So, how do you
deal with the perception,

00:30:07.780 --> 00:30:11.080
if you've received this, that
when you switch projects,

00:30:11.080 --> 00:30:13.030
that people might
think that you're

00:30:13.030 --> 00:30:17.317
unreliable or
flighty or unfocused?

00:30:17.317 --> 00:30:18.400
How do you deal with that?

00:30:18.400 --> 00:30:20.830
TANIA KATAN: I wrote an
entire book all about that.

00:30:20.830 --> 00:30:22.810
I'm being totally sincere.

00:30:22.810 --> 00:30:27.580
So, for years people would
say, so what do you do?

00:30:27.580 --> 00:30:31.840
And I was like, I am a curator
of everything-- whatever.

00:30:31.840 --> 00:30:38.020
I just made stuff up until I
realized that if I assessed

00:30:38.020 --> 00:30:43.150
my skills, my superpowers and
understood what those were,

00:30:43.150 --> 00:30:45.730
then it opened up
everything-- that I could

00:30:45.730 --> 00:30:47.830
go into any field, any job.

00:30:47.830 --> 00:30:50.080
So, the clarity
comes in knowing what

00:30:50.080 --> 00:30:52.000
you're bringing,
because you bring that

00:30:52.000 --> 00:30:53.470
to whatever situation.

00:30:53.470 --> 00:30:55.330
You bring that to
the supermarket.

00:30:55.330 --> 00:30:57.310
You bring that to
your family parties.

00:30:57.310 --> 00:30:59.300
You bring that to work.

00:30:59.300 --> 00:31:01.960
So, the sooner I
understood what I brought,

00:31:01.960 --> 00:31:05.160
the easier it was for me to
leap into different forms.

00:31:05.160 --> 00:31:08.620
And that's something-- we
obviously live in a system

00:31:08.620 --> 00:31:12.050
and a society
that's very siloed--

00:31:12.050 --> 00:31:14.740
and we have business
cards to prove that.

00:31:14.740 --> 00:31:17.680
You are a developer, you are--

00:31:17.680 --> 00:31:21.100
and I remember, I
was at a conference--

00:31:21.100 --> 00:31:23.680
I was speaking to 500 CIOs.

00:31:23.680 --> 00:31:24.880
Any CIOs here?

00:31:24.880 --> 00:31:25.450
Great.

00:31:25.450 --> 00:31:28.240
Let the jokes rip.

00:31:28.240 --> 00:31:32.680
So, I was in the
back of the room,

00:31:32.680 --> 00:31:37.300
and there were 500 CIOs
all dressed in suits--

00:31:37.300 --> 00:31:40.840
varying colors from
dark blue to black.

00:31:40.840 --> 00:31:43.630
And it was a Saturday, so they
didn't have to wear suits.

00:31:43.630 --> 00:31:45.460
So you know they were like this.

00:31:45.460 --> 00:31:49.075
And I was in the back watching
the speaker before me,

00:31:49.075 --> 00:31:50.950
and I was freaking out
because he was talking

00:31:50.950 --> 00:31:53.500
about like AI and IA and VR.

00:31:53.500 --> 00:31:57.640
And I'm like, unless they
want a monologue about TMI

00:31:57.640 --> 00:32:02.830
or UTI or BMWs, I had nothing.

00:32:02.830 --> 00:32:04.180
I was totally scared.

00:32:04.180 --> 00:32:07.990
And, to make matters
worse, he's killing it.

00:32:07.990 --> 00:32:10.240
And the CIOs are going wild.

00:32:10.240 --> 00:32:17.150
They're like-- and I'm
like, ah, where's the exit?

00:32:17.150 --> 00:32:19.760
And then the MC
grabs the microphone

00:32:19.760 --> 00:32:22.310
and he's like, oh,
let's thank Steve.

00:32:22.310 --> 00:32:26.000
And then we'd like to welcome
to the stage, Tania Katan,

00:32:26.000 --> 00:32:27.800
she is a CIO.

00:32:27.800 --> 00:32:32.540
And I'm like, oh, hell
no, I'm not a CIO.

00:32:32.540 --> 00:32:33.800
Another self-limiting belief.

00:32:33.800 --> 00:32:36.630
And I'm not a CIO.

00:32:36.630 --> 00:32:38.630
And then he grabs the
mic and he's like--

00:32:38.630 --> 00:32:40.880
chief inspiration officer.

00:32:40.880 --> 00:32:44.240
And I was like, oh, my god.

00:32:44.240 --> 00:32:45.895
So, what I learned from that--

00:32:45.895 --> 00:32:47.270
what I learned
from that moment--

00:32:47.270 --> 00:32:50.060
and I write about it because
it was so impactful--

00:32:50.060 --> 00:32:53.840
is that I thought when people
ask you what do you do,

00:32:53.840 --> 00:32:56.000
that it meant, what's
your job title?

00:32:56.000 --> 00:32:59.900
But, in that moment, I
realized, oh, it's my purpose.

00:32:59.900 --> 00:33:01.580
That's what I do.

00:33:01.580 --> 00:33:06.042
And the more certain and
comfortable you are with that,

00:33:06.042 --> 00:33:07.250
the more you can bring it in.

00:33:07.250 --> 00:33:08.875
And when somebody
says, what do you do?

00:33:08.875 --> 00:33:11.000
You can make up a job title.

00:33:11.000 --> 00:33:13.400
You can tell them, here's
my purpose, or sit down,

00:33:13.400 --> 00:33:16.420
I'm not going to give
you an elevator pitch.

00:33:16.420 --> 00:33:17.960
If you really want
to know, let me

00:33:17.960 --> 00:33:19.620
share what I do in the world.

00:33:19.620 --> 00:33:21.260
So, great question, thank you.

00:33:21.260 --> 00:33:23.990
AUDIENCE: So, for people who may
not consider themselves super

00:33:23.990 --> 00:33:27.440
creative, are there
tools or strategies

00:33:27.440 --> 00:33:30.710
that you advise to maybe
tap into creativity?

00:33:30.710 --> 00:33:33.800
You mentioned with
your campaign,

00:33:33.800 --> 00:33:37.160
you figured that out on a
walk or some kind of strategy

00:33:37.160 --> 00:33:40.040
where maybe we step away
from our day to day,

00:33:40.040 --> 00:33:42.760
not so creative work to
tap into the creative.

00:33:42.760 --> 00:33:43.760
TANIA KATAN: Absolutely.

00:33:43.760 --> 00:33:44.760
That's a great question.

00:33:44.760 --> 00:33:46.302
So, first of all,
I would like to say

00:33:46.302 --> 00:33:49.620
that creativity is defined as,
really, using your imagination.

00:33:49.620 --> 00:33:51.860
It's not about making art
or painting or duh duh duh.

00:33:51.860 --> 00:33:52.640
You could do that.

00:33:52.640 --> 00:33:54.650
But creativity is about
using your imagination.

00:33:54.650 --> 00:33:57.560
So, one thing that I recommend
in "Creative Trespassing"

00:33:57.560 --> 00:33:59.940
is to ditch school.

00:33:59.940 --> 00:34:01.400
Anybody ditch school as a kid?

00:34:01.400 --> 00:34:02.560
Yeah.

00:34:02.560 --> 00:34:04.100
We learned all
the skills we need

00:34:04.100 --> 00:34:05.990
to disrupt our patterns
and habits that

00:34:05.990 --> 00:34:07.650
are keeping us stuck.

00:34:07.650 --> 00:34:10.798
So, what I recommend is that
you get up from your desk--

00:34:10.798 --> 00:34:12.590
you don't have anything
to prove by working

00:34:12.590 --> 00:34:15.929
until you're sweating and you're
regretting the job you took--

00:34:15.929 --> 00:34:16.429
OK?

00:34:16.429 --> 00:34:17.360
Nothing to prove.

00:34:17.360 --> 00:34:20.420
Get up, take a five-minute,
10-minute walk.

00:34:20.420 --> 00:34:24.830
Stanford did a study on walking
and the impact of creativity.

00:34:24.830 --> 00:34:27.510
And it raises your
creativity by 60%.

00:34:27.510 --> 00:34:29.179
So, when you find
yourself trapped

00:34:29.179 --> 00:34:34.010
in trying to solve a problem
or just stuck in a routine,

00:34:34.010 --> 00:34:36.440
get up and go for a walk.

00:34:36.440 --> 00:34:39.139
And, in fact, there's something
called the Museum of Walking

00:34:39.139 --> 00:34:41.920
that I'm a board member of.

00:34:41.920 --> 00:34:42.753
And it's true.

00:34:42.753 --> 00:34:43.670
And you'll look it up.

00:34:43.670 --> 00:34:45.590
And, basically,
the museum exists

00:34:45.590 --> 00:34:49.670
outside of the wall-- there
are no walls to the museum.

00:34:49.670 --> 00:34:51.020
What?

00:34:51.020 --> 00:34:54.199
Why don't you Google that later.

00:34:54.199 --> 00:34:54.739
Oh, my god.

00:34:54.739 --> 00:34:56.659
I was trying to weave that in.

00:34:56.659 --> 00:34:58.010
Anyway.

00:34:58.010 --> 00:35:01.310
And then throughout the
book, I have these things

00:35:01.310 --> 00:35:03.350
called productive
disruptions, and they're

00:35:03.350 --> 00:35:08.150
exercises because I know that
when we disrupt these holding

00:35:08.150 --> 00:35:10.700
patterns, we
actually do more work

00:35:10.700 --> 00:35:13.580
and have more joy in
that state of creating--

00:35:13.580 --> 00:35:15.020
or co-creating work.

00:35:15.020 --> 00:35:16.115
Yeah, thank you.

00:35:16.115 --> 00:35:17.690
AUDIENCE: This
work is incredible,

00:35:17.690 --> 00:35:19.853
and you are a
phenomenal speaker.

00:35:19.853 --> 00:35:21.770
I'm sure you wake up
every morning with ideas,

00:35:21.770 --> 00:35:23.942
but what's next for you?

00:35:23.942 --> 00:35:25.900
You've written a book,
you're a public speaker.

00:35:25.900 --> 00:35:29.060
TANIA KATAN: Oh, my gosh.

00:35:29.060 --> 00:35:31.310
Gosh, this is where
I think my meditation

00:35:31.310 --> 00:35:33.080
practice has messed me up.

00:35:33.080 --> 00:35:35.150
What's next is what's now.

00:35:35.150 --> 00:35:37.760
I don't know what else
to say about that.

00:35:37.760 --> 00:35:41.780
What's next is me
continuing to speak.

00:35:41.780 --> 00:35:46.400
So, a lot of companies bring
me in to give talks and teach

00:35:46.400 --> 00:35:50.540
workshops on how do we use
creative skills for, maybe,

00:35:50.540 --> 00:35:53.630
theater or contemporary
art to innovate

00:35:53.630 --> 00:35:54.920
from within our companies.

00:35:54.920 --> 00:35:56.615
I would like to be
doing more and more--

00:35:56.615 --> 00:35:58.110
I could do that all day.

00:35:58.110 --> 00:36:00.200
And I think a lot of
people ask, well, you

00:36:00.200 --> 00:36:01.742
come from performance,
don't you want

00:36:01.742 --> 00:36:02.930
to perform again on a stage?

00:36:02.930 --> 00:36:05.150
And, to me, the
most impactful work

00:36:05.150 --> 00:36:07.555
is being an outsider
on the inside.

00:36:07.555 --> 00:36:09.680
And then you quickly realize
when you're like, hey,

00:36:09.680 --> 00:36:11.310
you guys, I do wild things.

00:36:11.310 --> 00:36:12.470
And they're like, I do too.

00:36:12.470 --> 00:36:14.720
Oh, my god, there are creative
trespassers everywhere.

00:36:14.720 --> 00:36:18.050
And, so, really, the end game
with "Creative Trespassing"

00:36:18.050 --> 00:36:22.040
is to cause a creative
revolution inside our bodies,

00:36:22.040 --> 00:36:23.880
our minds, and our cubicles.

00:36:23.880 --> 00:36:24.380
That's all.

00:36:27.680 --> 00:36:28.300
Thank you.

00:36:28.300 --> 00:36:28.800
Yeah.

00:36:31.410 --> 00:36:32.638
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:36:32.638 --> 00:36:34.430
With the theme of
International Women's Day

00:36:34.430 --> 00:36:36.860
being "Balance for Better,"
can you talk about what balance

00:36:36.860 --> 00:36:37.443
means for you?

00:36:37.443 --> 00:36:38.720
TANIA KATAN: Oh.

00:36:38.720 --> 00:36:41.200
Sleeping eight hours.

00:36:41.200 --> 00:36:41.820
You know what?

00:36:41.820 --> 00:36:45.470
So, as in my introduction,
you learned I actually

00:36:45.470 --> 00:36:49.310
have gone through cancer two
times-- one when I was 21,

00:36:49.310 --> 00:36:51.520
one was when I was 31 years old.

00:36:51.520 --> 00:36:54.200
And when you've
endured an illness,

00:36:54.200 --> 00:36:56.360
or if you're living
with an illness,

00:36:56.360 --> 00:37:00.680
you are painfully aware
of the body and the mind

00:37:00.680 --> 00:37:02.210
and the connection
or the moments

00:37:02.210 --> 00:37:04.790
when one wants to
disconnect, because it's

00:37:04.790 --> 00:37:06.890
painful and uncomfortable.

00:37:06.890 --> 00:37:10.040
And, after enduring those
two bouts of cancer,

00:37:10.040 --> 00:37:13.500
I realized I needed to
take care of myself.

00:37:13.500 --> 00:37:15.450
So, even though I'm
sort of on book tour

00:37:15.450 --> 00:37:19.650
and I'm going back and back,
how I care for myself is I

00:37:19.650 --> 00:37:21.540
eat well.

00:37:21.540 --> 00:37:25.170
And I'm open to dinners
being paid for by anyone.

00:37:25.170 --> 00:37:27.160
Then I eat better.

00:37:27.160 --> 00:37:28.890
I eat well.

00:37:28.890 --> 00:37:31.630
I try to walk every day.

00:37:31.630 --> 00:37:34.770
And I say, try, because
sometimes I'm limited in time.

00:37:34.770 --> 00:37:36.570
But even then, I
literally will walk around

00:37:36.570 --> 00:37:38.310
like a hotel parking lot.

00:37:38.310 --> 00:37:41.700
My body feels better
when it's walked.

00:37:41.700 --> 00:37:46.170
And also I meditate and
that makes me really--

00:37:46.170 --> 00:37:48.600
that makes me consider
what's in front of me

00:37:48.600 --> 00:37:50.310
rather than what's ahead of me.

00:37:50.310 --> 00:37:51.810
And I think that's
really important,

00:37:51.810 --> 00:37:54.310
because if I'm not occupying
this space right here and right

00:37:54.310 --> 00:37:56.640
now, I actually don't know
what's going to be next.

00:37:56.640 --> 00:37:59.160
I won't be open to what's
next and I want to be open.

00:37:59.160 --> 00:38:00.690
So, yeah, that's it.

00:38:00.690 --> 00:38:01.620
Great question.

00:38:01.620 --> 00:38:02.475
Thank you.

00:38:02.475 --> 00:38:04.570
AUDIENCE: First of
all, great talk.

00:38:04.570 --> 00:38:07.800
Thank you so much for
sharing your story with us.

00:38:07.800 --> 00:38:10.950
I do feel like you have
the answers for everything.

00:38:10.950 --> 00:38:15.780
But I wanted to know, did you
ever experience self-doubt

00:38:15.780 --> 00:38:17.010
in each of your journeys?

00:38:17.010 --> 00:38:19.565
And, if yes, how
did you combat that?

00:38:19.565 --> 00:38:21.210
TANIA KATAN: Oh, yes.

00:38:21.210 --> 00:38:21.878
All the time.

00:38:21.878 --> 00:38:22.920
And, in fact, what just--

00:38:22.920 --> 00:38:25.320
I'll go with the first thing
that popped into my head.

00:38:25.320 --> 00:38:28.795
When I started my job
at the museum, I mean,

00:38:28.795 --> 00:38:30.420
I don't have an art
history background,

00:38:30.420 --> 00:38:31.710
I've never been a curator.

00:38:31.710 --> 00:38:35.110
Like, I was the weirdest
choice for that job.

00:38:35.110 --> 00:38:38.410
And so, I was freaking
out the day before

00:38:38.410 --> 00:38:41.320
and I combated it by
saying, what do I wear?

00:38:41.320 --> 00:38:43.170
How do I look arty?

00:38:43.170 --> 00:38:44.970
How do I look like
I work in a museum?

00:38:44.970 --> 00:38:47.820
Because my big,
self-limiting belief

00:38:47.820 --> 00:38:52.050
since I was little until
now was, I don't fit in.

00:38:52.050 --> 00:38:53.490
I don't belong here.

00:38:53.490 --> 00:38:55.630
That has been a
refrain in the past.

00:38:55.630 --> 00:38:57.400
So, I'm aware of that.

00:38:57.400 --> 00:38:59.370
And so, what I do
is the same thing

00:38:59.370 --> 00:39:01.140
I've learned in theater school--

00:39:01.140 --> 00:39:04.750
you have to see an audience, you
have to listen to an audience,

00:39:04.750 --> 00:39:07.677
you have to decide what you're
going to give to an audience.

00:39:07.677 --> 00:39:09.510
And I don't mean this
in a performative way,

00:39:09.510 --> 00:39:11.010
I mean this is like
an interpersonal way.

00:39:11.010 --> 00:39:12.690
So I'm like, OK, they're
a contemporary art--

00:39:12.690 --> 00:39:14.970
so I just sort of assessed
the situation and thought,

00:39:14.970 --> 00:39:20.460
I will wear a blue shirt
and an orange blazer

00:39:20.460 --> 00:39:24.540
and red glasses and
some funky sneakers.

00:39:24.540 --> 00:39:26.970
Yes, I looked like
a cartoon character,

00:39:26.970 --> 00:39:32.070
but it made me feel like I was
embodying the spirit of art.

00:39:32.070 --> 00:39:34.560
So, that's what I do.

00:39:34.560 --> 00:39:37.890
And, also, I was
recently telling

00:39:37.890 --> 00:39:42.300
a story for "The Moth" in
front of 2,000 human beings.

00:39:42.300 --> 00:39:44.880
And I hadn't done a
storytelling in that form,

00:39:44.880 --> 00:39:46.140
and I was scared--

00:39:46.140 --> 00:39:47.070
super scared.

00:39:47.070 --> 00:39:48.930
So, here's what I did
in that situation.

00:39:48.930 --> 00:39:51.240
I'm about to go on,
and I say to myself--

00:39:51.240 --> 00:39:53.670
Tania, if you pass out,
you don't have to go on.

00:39:56.220 --> 00:39:59.040
"Creative Trespassing."

00:39:59.040 --> 00:40:02.420
And so, this is something I've
learned from one of my teachers

00:40:02.420 --> 00:40:05.400
and from reading
and watching her--

00:40:05.400 --> 00:40:09.175
Pema Chodron-- is that when
you are experiencing fear,

00:40:09.175 --> 00:40:10.800
it's sort of the last
thing on our list

00:40:10.800 --> 00:40:13.890
to do to like embrace it.

00:40:13.890 --> 00:40:16.000
And she's like, go into it.

00:40:16.000 --> 00:40:17.820
Barrel headfirst into fear.

00:40:17.820 --> 00:40:20.662
And then you realize,
oh, it's not so bad.

00:40:20.662 --> 00:40:21.870
I came out on the other side.

00:40:21.870 --> 00:40:23.412
We always come out
on the other side.

00:40:23.412 --> 00:40:26.010
You know that, and that's why
the leap of faith is important.

00:40:26.010 --> 00:40:28.050
The middle part,
you're like, ah.

00:40:28.050 --> 00:40:30.600
But you always know that
you're going to land, right?

00:40:30.600 --> 00:40:32.950
And that it's going
to be more than OK.

00:40:32.950 --> 00:40:36.738
So, that's what I do.

00:40:36.738 --> 00:40:37.567
AUDIENCE: Hey.

00:40:37.567 --> 00:40:39.900
So, it's really cool to hear
about how confident you are

00:40:39.900 --> 00:40:42.950
and your purpose and what
you bring to the table.

00:40:42.950 --> 00:40:45.450
And you've talked about
how it's important to be

00:40:45.450 --> 00:40:46.260
grounded in that.

00:40:46.260 --> 00:40:48.070
How do you get to
that point, though?

00:40:48.070 --> 00:40:49.470
If you could talk to that.

00:40:49.470 --> 00:40:51.387
TANIA KATAN: Yeah, that's
an awesome question.

00:40:51.387 --> 00:40:54.930
So, first of all, the way in
which we write books, the way

00:40:54.930 --> 00:40:56.070
in which we live lives--

00:40:56.070 --> 00:40:58.260
all of it is a practice.

00:40:58.260 --> 00:40:59.535
I approach it as a practice.

00:40:59.535 --> 00:41:00.410
I'm not the only one.

00:41:00.410 --> 00:41:03.180
There's a practice of
meditation-- doctors practice

00:41:03.180 --> 00:41:05.440
medicine.

00:41:05.440 --> 00:41:08.610
Those who play
instruments practice.

00:41:08.610 --> 00:41:11.850
So, when we think about
it as a practice--

00:41:11.850 --> 00:41:14.190
and if it's a
practice, guess what?

00:41:14.190 --> 00:41:15.990
It's never going to
be perfect, right?

00:41:15.990 --> 00:41:17.170
It's a practice.

00:41:17.170 --> 00:41:20.640
So, if we think of
building skills around,

00:41:20.640 --> 00:41:22.050
I want to be more
curious, I want

00:41:22.050 --> 00:41:23.970
to be more confident--
as practicing,

00:41:23.970 --> 00:41:26.220
I'm going to try on what
confident looks like or feels

00:41:26.220 --> 00:41:27.400
like to me today.

00:41:27.400 --> 00:41:29.490
OK, that didn't work.

00:41:29.490 --> 00:41:31.590
That's OK, but one
moment within that,

00:41:31.590 --> 00:41:33.120
I did feel a little confident.

00:41:33.120 --> 00:41:35.412
Then you remember-- then you
try it again the next day,

00:41:35.412 --> 00:41:36.328
and then the next day.

00:41:36.328 --> 00:41:38.700
And then what happens is
something I learned in theater

00:41:38.700 --> 00:41:40.200
which is muscle memory--

00:41:40.200 --> 00:41:40.860
guess what?

00:41:40.860 --> 00:41:42.840
Your body knows what to do.

00:41:42.840 --> 00:41:46.830
It shows up without your
mind messing things up.

00:41:46.830 --> 00:41:48.900
So, you have to
practice embodying

00:41:48.900 --> 00:41:52.440
what it is you
want to be and how

00:41:52.440 --> 00:41:57.020
you want to be in the world
every day a little bit.

00:41:57.020 --> 00:42:00.680
Is that helpful?

00:42:00.680 --> 00:42:05.066
I think we're going to
take two more questions.

00:42:05.066 --> 00:42:07.690
AUDIENCE: How did you
come to find your purpose?

00:42:07.690 --> 00:42:09.190
And what tools did
you use and which

00:42:09.190 --> 00:42:11.760
ones did you like most of all?

00:42:11.760 --> 00:42:15.010
TANIA KATAN: So, I've written
about this, because it's

00:42:15.010 --> 00:42:17.830
taken me lots of tools.

00:42:17.830 --> 00:42:22.570
And, in "Creative Trespassing,"
an exercise that I have is

00:42:22.570 --> 00:42:24.220
it's called, write
your fight song.

00:42:24.220 --> 00:42:26.020
But, really, it's a manifesto.

00:42:26.020 --> 00:42:27.910
Who here knows what
a manifesto is?

00:42:27.910 --> 00:42:32.290
Yeah, it's a powerful
declaration of your purpose--

00:42:32.290 --> 00:42:34.660
of your why and your how.

00:42:34.660 --> 00:42:37.890
Like, yes, I declare
this, and here's

00:42:37.890 --> 00:42:39.890
how I'm going to actually
do something about it.

00:42:39.890 --> 00:42:42.700
So, it's not
passive, it's active.

00:42:42.700 --> 00:42:44.170
And so, I've found my--

00:42:44.170 --> 00:42:47.300
I say, purpi, because I don't
think we have one purpose.

00:42:47.300 --> 00:42:50.750
And I think that this is also
one of those system silo traps

00:42:50.750 --> 00:42:51.850
we find ourselves in.

00:42:51.850 --> 00:42:53.710
And I've definitely
found myself in it.

00:42:53.710 --> 00:42:56.350
I majored in theater, how come
I can't get a job in theater?

00:42:56.350 --> 00:42:58.420
I have no purpose--

00:42:58.420 --> 00:42:59.370
and scene.

00:42:59.370 --> 00:43:03.400
I'm using my degree.

00:43:03.400 --> 00:43:06.670
And I've often found
myself in that trap,

00:43:06.670 --> 00:43:10.590
and then I realize, oh,
wait, my purpose is--

00:43:10.590 --> 00:43:14.230
and another indicator is,
what really enlivens you when

00:43:14.230 --> 00:43:16.840
you're in the act of doing it?

00:43:16.840 --> 00:43:20.080
So, if you are coding and
you're like, holy shit,

00:43:20.080 --> 00:43:22.870
this is so awesome, this
feels good and every fiber--

00:43:22.870 --> 00:43:26.440
or you're a problem
solver, you're a presenter

00:43:26.440 --> 00:43:28.040
and you're like, I like people.

00:43:28.040 --> 00:43:29.780
I like when they ask questions.

00:43:29.780 --> 00:43:31.970
Those are all indicators
of your purpose.

00:43:31.970 --> 00:43:37.030
So, I guess, buy the
book and do the exercise?

00:43:37.030 --> 00:43:41.770
And also-- and also, just
know that you monitor--

00:43:41.770 --> 00:43:45.640
you're the conductor of
the experiment of you,

00:43:45.640 --> 00:43:47.710
and so you can be
aware of situations

00:43:47.710 --> 00:43:50.530
where you feel like this
makes me feel alive,

00:43:50.530 --> 00:43:52.780
and it enlivens those around me.

00:43:52.780 --> 00:43:55.630
Maybe this is one
of my purposes.

00:43:55.630 --> 00:43:56.410
Great question.

00:43:56.410 --> 00:43:57.178
Thank you.

00:43:57.178 --> 00:43:59.470
OK, we had a super quick--
we had a creative trespasser

00:43:59.470 --> 00:44:00.130
question.

00:44:00.130 --> 00:44:03.130
Didn't need a
microphone-- love that.

00:44:03.130 --> 00:44:05.710
How often do I burst into song?

00:44:05.710 --> 00:44:08.260
Like in my daily life?

00:44:08.260 --> 00:44:12.730
Oh, well, I am known far and
wide as the monotone wonder.

00:44:12.730 --> 00:44:14.980
So, I don't typically--

00:44:14.980 --> 00:44:18.810
but I burst into song always
when I'm on a road trip

00:44:18.810 --> 00:44:21.070
by myself.

00:44:21.070 --> 00:44:22.062
And I'm like, oh-ahh--

00:44:25.240 --> 00:44:28.300
because I hit all
the right notes when

00:44:28.300 --> 00:44:31.090
it's just an audience of me.

00:44:31.090 --> 00:44:33.170
But I dance all the time.

00:44:33.170 --> 00:44:36.610
So like in supermarkets
and conferences and things

00:44:36.610 --> 00:44:39.160
like that-- just,
inadvertently even sometimes.

00:44:39.160 --> 00:44:40.780
I'm like what?

00:44:40.780 --> 00:44:42.430
That's awesome.

00:44:42.430 --> 00:44:44.824
Thanks for asking.

